They see the 2027 free cash flow yield on equity at 38%, which is remarkably close to what I model.

full_text:
They had a €7 price target on July 2, when the share price was €5,14. This implies a 28% FCF yield for 2027 on their price target. 

Frankly, I have no idea in what world a basically unlevered company should trade at a 28% FCF yield. 

In my model I have very significant FCF growth for years to come after 2027. If we assume a FCF yield of 7% in 2027, which I still find very steep, share price should be €28 at a minimum. 

Easy to justify €50 in 2027 if JPM and my assumptions play out.

Collapsing birth rates are slowly but surely becoming a mainstream problem. 

Here’s my hot take:
Our social / retirement system only works with the young taking care of the old and paying for the old through taxes. 

The childless found a way for arbitrage - a risk less gain. Childless people are at every point in life financially better off than if they had kids all else equal:

less expenses, more savings, more retirement income and financial assets during retirement. 

Essentially, the childless are free riding other people’s kids. 

To fix this, it must be financially at the very least indifferent whether or not to have kids. Until we reach an equilibrium, those with kids should be better off. 

The country that gets this first will survive long term.
name: Value Investigator

full_text:

But the economic pain of having many kids becomes harder to overcome (just check out the rent of a 5 room apartment in major cities). At the same time, having no kids is more and more of a no brainer, also as the future looks rationally darker. 

The earlier we steer against the economic madness, the better.

full_text:
Very „interesting“ election outcome in Germany:

CDU/CSU has won, but with just 28.5%. Their chancellor candidate Merz, famous for his anti-AFD firewall stance will now have only one option:
A coalition with both, SPD & the Green party, both of which have unanimously rejected Merz’ proposal for a change in immigration policy. 

This is a disaster in the making for both Merz and Germany. Essentially the new government would be even less stable than the prior Ampel coalition which was the most disliked in Germanys recent history. 

Frankly, this scenario would make me extremely bearish on Germany and also Europe. 

However, I see a small glimmer of hope. Given that the situation is as impossible as it is, the alternative that had been ruled out becomes more attractive: A coalition between CDU/CSU and AfD (20.7%) would be strongly aligned in terms of immigration and economic policy. 

This could not happen under Merz, as he tied his persona to the firewall. However, I expect pressure on Merz will get very strong as he won’t be able to form acceptable coalition compromises. Not acceptable for his election promises, not acceptable for SPD and Greens, and not acceptable for German voters. 

This moment will offer a window of opportunity for Markus Söder from CDU/CSU to become Chancellor by tearing down the firewall and form a coalition with AFD. Söder can be described as extremely power hungry and opportunistic. Characteristics that will be required to tear down the firewall and build the coalition Germany needs. 

Below a picture of Söder with Vance at the Munich Security Conference. Personally, I like Söder a lot as a politician and I believe he is much more aligned with the unwokening of the US than Merz. Without doubt, this turn of events would also be a chance to save US/Germany relationship which Merz has to my shock absolutely buried in todays post election interview.
name: Value Investigator

full_text: Germany voted for a u-turn in illegal immigration and CDU won the election by promising AFD policies. \n\nCoalition negotiations have ended and it is clear what Germany will get is nothing more than a “reduction light” of illegal immigration.
name: Value Investigator

full_text:
From the CDU's point of view, the wording in the exploratory paper is powerful enough to give the impression of an asylum change. An uprising of the base and the deputies is thus unlikely to take place for the time being.

But, big BUT:

All Merz announcements are linguistically so softened that not much of them will remain.

1. "Rejection of ALL on the first day" becomes "rejection in consultation with European partners by all means of the rule of law, including asylum applications." Means: Germany will only do what the EU allows and what is supported by neighboring countries. Will Merz thus, as promised, instruct the BMI to reject all illegal migrants at all borders? No.

2. Illegal migration should no longer be "ended", but "effectively pushed back".

3. What really happens can be read in the family reunification. It is suspended ONLY for persons entitled to subsidiary protection and only "for a limited time". That's 12,000 out of about 130,000 per year. Where it can be measured with hard numbers, the "asylum term" means: ten percent less migration, the rest may expressly come further.

4. Gross defeat for the Union in citizenship. The new law of the SPD and the Greens should remain explicit, the German passport will continue to be smed on the fast track.

5. For inexplicable reasons, 25,000 migrants per year are still allowed to enter Germany from the Western Balkans (instead of the previous 50,000). Again in hard numbers: Where you could easily reduce by one hundred percent, you reduce by 50 percent.

6. According to the wording, rejections at the border of asylum seekers are only possible if Poland, the Czech Republic, Austria, etc. agree.

CONCLUSION: Maybe it was no longer in it (and in the coalition negotiations this is diluted even further), but this has very little to do with the "unnegotiable" conditions of Friedrich Merz.

FORECAST: Illegal migration will continue, reduced by approx. 25 percent.
name: Value Investigator
